poem:
**The Frabjous Flare of Interference**

‘Twas blipping, and the snarl‑snick waves did blench;  
They flutter‑crackle through the garble‑guff, a drench;  
All whir‑snorts were jammed‑waver in a blench;  
And shiver‑spang the static‑spume did drench.

**The Creepling**

'Twas brillig, and the slithy creeps
Did gyre and gimble through the walls;

The Printerjam

In printhour, when the rollers creak and fumble-gleam,
And tray-sprites wheeze in winding queues that slip and seam;
All deskfolk bumble by the feed with breath and bated thumb,
Beware the Jamjaw, rumblecrimp and drum!

Beware the Jamjaw, clerk of mine! The teeth that crimp and snag!
The curl that snap-fangs catch, the tray that tugs and nag!
Shun fuser-fiends and sprocket-snaps and toner-bitten blight!

He seized his spanner-sabre, lean, and leaned toward the maw;
He peered into the crooked chute where folded papers gnaw;
Left tug, right pry—he plucked the knot of crimped and clattery night,
And, as the Printerjam unbent, it gave a slobber-sight.

One-two! One-two! Through nip and nap he tore;
He wrestled folded leaf and spit the crumpled core;
He flicked the lever—clack!—the rollers sighed and stilled their jams;
He flung the final scrap away, and quelled the Jamjaw's clams.

Back hummed the trays with orderly streams of black on white anew;
He bore the printout bounty home; the toner-smile grew true;
"O trumple day!" the office sang, "the duplex flows again!"
And all the stapled pages lay without a wrinkle's reign.

The Musicroomwock

’Twas brumpling in the music-room, the candle-gong did swing;
The tablorn sighed on velvet rails, the metronomes did cling;
All mimsy were the harp-snarks, and the windlish flutes aflute;
Beware the Musicroomwock, my child, the beast of bolted lute!

He strode to where the piano-reef lay snoring, keys all white and black,
And in the corner, brash and bulb, the Bassjaw opened slack;
Its brassly teeth went tootle-grin, its cymflaps broke the air;
It hummed the hollow, clanging thrum of counterpoint despair.

“O father, see the timp-snout rise, the cello-spine undulate!”
The bowlings hissed, the strings did stitch a skein of syncopate;
But forth he went with strum-sword drawn — a gleaming quarter-note —
He whistled low a glimmer-song and struck the organ-throat.

The Musicroomwock did shudder-snap, its valves in whirlpools span,
It frothed a hundred fandangoes, it staggered, staccato-fanned;
He pluckled there a bravely chord, a tremor, twine, and swoop,
Till Bassjaw flung his last bass-bream and sank to timbre's loop.

And then! — the shelved-scores, they danced; the metronomes they beamed;
The harp-snarks winked their silver tongues; the flutelets softly dreamed;
“O son! the Musicroomwock is felled! the studio is free!”
He brought the tune-home, blythe and blest, a victor's vibrato-glee.

So when the lamp-gongs brumple low and midnight keys conspire,
Beware the hush that swells to roar, the monster's minor fire;
But arm yourself with steady hand, with cadence, pulse, and pluck—
The Musicroomwock will falter, felled by one true struck.

Underpass Echo, a Jabberwocky-Tinged Ballad

'Twas underpass, and the echolights did gyre and gimble in the gloam;
All slithy clangmotes were the borogoves of chrome;
And the mome-echoes outgrabe in the hush of stone;
One vorpal-treader strode forth to greet the echo's doom;

Beware the Snickering Dreem, with a sighing-lilt of bone;
He waved a vorpal-baton and peered into the tunnel's tomb;
The echo crooned, 'O frabjous boom!' and swelled the echo-bloom;
And the underpass whispered softly, 'Twick-twick,' through the gloom.

Dawnfog in the Jabbermire

’Twas dawnfog, and the slithy mists did gyre and gleam;
Mimsy fields were morrow-misted, roofs wore gauzy dream;
Frabjous zephyrs whisked the hushlow lanes awry,
And dew-wisp banners fluttered ’neath a waking sky.

The borogroves blinked softly, hedges sighed in light;
Mizzlewinks glittered on each pane, and roads grew bright;
Beams, like mummer-flutters, drifted through the sleepy town,
Till fog withdrew its cloak and day wore golden crown.

Desire-Path in the Wabe

'Twas brillig, and desyre-paths did gyre and gimble in the wabe;
All mimsy were the borogoves,
And the mome raths outgrabe.
Desire-paths whispered, "come, wander, and crave."

Beware the snick-snap steps that shortcut through the night;
The cross-lane curve that curls and sighs and grins;
For every tread that scrawls the grass just right
Becomes a line the world can’t pretend to mend.

Desyre-paths chortle in the pale starlight's seam;
They slip through hedges, whorl through bricks and foam;
They braid the air with cartoonish dream,
And lead the heart along a road called home.

Then follow forth, O traveler with careful feet;
Let worn curves write the map you seek to find;
The desyre-path will bloom where longing meets
And guide you softly to where you’re inclined.

The Boardroom Wabe

'Twas brillig, and the slithy toves
Did gyre and gimble in the boardroom-wabe;
All mimsy were the memos, and the minutes outgrabe.

Beware the Zoomer-gnash, with its lit mic glare,
The jaws that bite the budgets and the claws that snare;
And the mome raths of sticky-notes there
That scribble-snap the margins of morning air.

One, two—the chairs clack and clatter like keys;
The projector sighs in a pale, glimmer-blur;
Whiteboard scribbles flurb and fizz in the breeze,
While laptops whirr, and coffee sighs in a stir.

Come to the agenda, weigh the risk and worth;
Let data prance in dotted lines;
And let the action-items sprint from birth to birth
Until decisions dawn in tidy signs.

The door sighs shut; the clock ticks slow;
The glassy room hums in a hollow tune;
And in that conference-charmed afterglow,
The plan takes root and blooms by noon.

The Music-Room Jabberwock

'Twas brillig, and the timbre-toves did gyre and gimble in the wabe;
All mimsy were the score-nests, and the chair-shelves outgrabe.
Beware the glissopede, and the treble-gnar with fretting-fangs;
He flogs the moonbeam notes and splashes hush with clangs.

From piano-pool and violin-vale the wind-riffs drift and blend;
The metronome click-clacks like a clockwork comet's friend.
The guitar-winged shadows skim the velvet air with spark and glow;
And every shelf-horn whispers in a tongue no mortal knows.

Then pedal-petals sigh and whirl; the drums go whisper-wide;
A chorus of brass-bells opens, letting daylight hide.
"Sing, scribble-scrape!" the room proclaims in honeyed, odd rhyme;
"For music thrives wherever nonsense blooms with chime."

The Creep in the Wabe
'Twas creepish night, and slithy creeps did gyre and gimble in the wabe;
All mimsy borogoves fluttered by, and the mome raths outgrabe.
Beware the Creep, my friend—the glimmer-brow and shadow-sly;
He whispers through the narrow halls where moonlight dares not fly.
He comes with snerk-snout and murmur-grin, with eyes of flicker-flame;
He threads the creak of floor and door—each step a whisper-name.
One, two! One, two! and through the gap of dusky loom;
The Creep skims by, a silver-snick of doom and gloom.
O Creep! O Creep! What noggin-knack you keep in your throat of night?
You nibble at the corners of the mind until the room forgets the light.

The Umbrella in the Wabe

'Twas drimble-wet, and umbrellalings did glint and glim in the wabe;
Rib-nets clicked softly—clip-clop—a rain-song on the brim;
Cloth-sails flutterflicked with skyskein hues, bright as a ribbon of flame;
The handle thrimble-thrummed a lullaby to the wandering wind;
Snick-snack raindrops pattered on the edge in a merry tick-tock tune;
And the umbrella woke with a bow, a rainbow-lilt for the rain's parade.

The Science-Fair Jabberwock

'Twas glow-gleam noon in the science-hall, posters in bright rows;
Beaker-bells fizz-winked softly, and data-sparks flew and glowed.
Robobots whir-wirred with copper-brain gleams, charts clacked in time;
While chalk-dust constellations mapped the crowd’s curious rhyme.

Borogoves of curiosity flitted through glossy aisles;
Quarkle-stars twinkled on grids wearing mischievous, clever smiles.
A tove-tuner hummed, rotor-lashed with glassy tunes;
Gimcrack-wands stitched ideas into rainbow-bright runes.

Judges with clip-boards clattered, tallying each brave claim;
They hailed fizzbang notions and the patient, careful aim.
Diorama-crescendos bloomed from cardboard-bright bays;
Sun-prism dioramas glowed like miniature dawns in blaze.

From solar sleds to magnet moons and microscope rain;
The hall became a ship of wonder, sailing through data’s plain.
When bells tolled thrice, the dreamers bowed with gleam;
For science crowned their curious minds with a starry stream.

Monte Carlo Jabberwocky

'Twas glintish, and the toves did gyre and gimble in the wabe;
All mimsy casinos glittered, and chandeliers did crave.
"Beware the Monte Carlo-jabber," whispered the maître d' in blue;
"One bite of glitter-night and fortune will gobble you true."

From the slithy-toves the cards did bumfuzzle bright;
They snicker-snack at blackjack, they whizz with neon light.
The borogoves chirped; the jabberwock's tail fizzed in the night;
It gnash'd its lime-lip mouth with a velvet-laden bite.

He came with snicker-snack dice and a bottle of moon;
The dice went clatter-clack, like boats on a silver lagoon.
"One-two!" cried the croupier, "the night is yours to keep!"
And through the harbor's gleam ship-shapes slid and fell asleep.

Monte Carlo woke with a sigh of electric lace;
The sea wore a silver scarf, the hills a jade-green face.
The Grand Prix roared softly in the distance, far and sweet;
And the wabe-breeze hummed a coin-lilted, soft-vibrant beat.

Thus spun the night in coin-bright air till the dawn grew slow;
The jabberwock of luck dissolved in rose and gold's glow.
And all who wandered there wore dreams like gowns of wine,
In Monte Carlo's trance of glitter, where luck and fancy twine.

The Brillig Shutter of the Film Kamera

'Twas brillig, and the shutterbloom did gyre and gimble in the wabe;
All mimsy were the frames, as emulsion-snakes wound the grain.
Beware the Bandersnatch Lens, with teeth of glass and glare;
One sly click from its maw, and daylight dissolves to cinema air.

The film-coil hissed, reelsnakes twined on copper-spined rings;
The aperture yawns wide, a hungry moon of light it brings.
Click-snap! The moments spill like moths of amber flame;
And time is bottled in a frame, to wake when next we name.

Emulsion sprites skitter in the red lamp’s patient glow;
Negatives dream in gray-soft sleep, where silent stories grow.
Wind the dial softly, O keeper, let dawn be born anew;
For every tender blink the world is born again for you.

The Music-Room Jabberwocky

’Twas brillig, and the music-room did gyre and gimble in the wabe;
All mimsy were the metronomes, and the keys outgrabe;
Beware the Crescendo-Wock, my dear, the chords that crave and crave;
And snicker-snack the staff-walls where the shadow-staves behave.

One, two! One, two! The tympani-tops did jabber and jiggle;
The fipple-flutes fizz-buzzed; the harps did prance and wiggle;
The piano-nimbus opened wide and showered rainbow-twigs to giggle;
While chairs and chandeliers dripped music like a dream-tassel giggle.

O frabjous day! Callooh! Callay! The scales did moot and mingle;
The lute-lobes shimmered; the strings did tingle and jingle;
The bassoon-boughs bowed low as moonlight drizzled on the single;
And the music-room glowed with a glow that sang, and sang, and springle.

The borogoves of sound slipped through the door with a sigh;
The rhythmic-wraiths hopped along the carpet's sly;
The wall-clock hummed a ditty while the lamps winked wry;
Till morning came, and with it a lullaby in shy.

The Slithy Wings of the Stage

'Twas hush in the wings, and the flyloft sighed in a frabjous tune;
Ropes muttered sly chimes, and lamps winked behind a silvered noon;
The jabberwings flapped their lidflaps, tuning the hush for the cue's parade;
And velvet curtains breathed prologue, waiting to spill the masquerade.

Behind the wing-doors, tackle-tangles twined in a ghostly rhyme;
Pulley-strings clacked crisp as moth-wings tapping out the drum of time;
A chorus of hinges crooned a lilting tune, a secret mime in chime;
Till the wings unfurl their velvet breath and cradle dreams in rhyme.

The Creep in the Wabe

'Twas crepish, and the slithy toves did gyre and gimble in the wabe;
All mimsy borogoves were the mome-raths outgrabe.
"Beware the Creep," the frumious shadows cried in pale moonlight;
He glides through hedges, zip-zap-zoom, and steals the hush of night.

His whisper-wings rustle the grass, his frost-bit eyes a-dazzle;
He ticks the hours with tick-tock-flick, and bends your will to frazzle.
One gulp of fear, one hush of sleep, and courage withers thin;
But sing a brave, frabjous verse, and Creep slips back within.

The Awl in the Wabe

'Twas glintish and sly, the awl did glide and gimble in the wabe;
Borogoves blinkled blorpish, and mome raths outgrabe.
With snick-snick steel, the awl did stitch the shadow seam—
A twinkling, clang-lilt lullaby that stitched the dream.

Oft wind-snap quirkled by, with flim and dringle flake;
The awl wore a hat of tinny light and never looked back, awake.
Beware the seam that yawns too wide, the needle's chilly kiss;
For in that yawning place of stitchy night, a cut would hiss.

Morning yawns, a yawp of day, the wabe grows gray and wan;
The awl folds up its silver song and rests till night is drawn.
Yet every thread in every hedge and corner, bright with gleam,
Whispers of the awl in the wabe—still stitching through a dream.

Desire-Path in the Wabe

'Twas brillig, and the slithy toves did gyre and gimble in the wabe;
All mimsy were the borogoves, and the mome raths outgrabe.
'Beware the desire-path, my son! The jaws that bite, the claws that catch;
Beware the frumious urge that gnaws the gate and snatches at the latch.'
He took his vorpal-wish in hand; long time the despath sought to bend;
So rested he by the brook of Want, and pondered where the wants would end.
And, as in uffish thought he stood, the despath-prints did twine and call his name;
One, two! one, two! and through the desiring-path he walked, aflame.
'Twas brillig, and the slithy toves did gyre and gimble in the wabe;
All mimsy were the borogoves, and the mome raths outgrabe.
The path whispered, "Follow me; dream and desire will never cease;"
So the seeker followed the worn line, until longing found its peace.

Morning Fog in the Wabe

'Twas mornling, and the fog did gyre and flimble in the wabe;
The roofs wore dew-dust halos, and chimneys coughed a sleepy brume.
The sun snoodled behind a dribble-drape of gray,
While fogwobblers driftled down the lanes in soft, lilting gloom.

Puddle-mirrors yawned and whispered of sidle-stars and ache;
Lamp-lights blinked pale halos, crooning to the waking brake.
The hedges wore lace of mist, and doorways whispered, Come;
A muffled thrush of morning hummed in the dawn's low hum.

Then snortle-wind teased the mist from fence and fen;
The town awoke, yawning into the light again.
Thus fog in jabberfizz lace would twine with day,
Till sun pricks through and chases all the fog away.

Underpass Echo

'Twas dimplish, and the underpass did gyre and gimble in the gloom;
The mimsy lamps flickered, dripdrizzle tapping doom.
From archway-nooks the echo-gnarl began to loom;
Brazzle-bawl and fizzmirth stitched syllables in the room.
It whispered through vents in slither-snap and shadow-swoon;
And boing-bloom whistled back from brick and rain-dim tomb.
O frabjous sound! the tunnel wore a tired silver moon;
Where tires tap-tap and distant cars hum a wane tune.
'Come closer,' crooned the echo, 'to hear me croon and croon;'
But when you step near, the walls lean in and swoon.
Gloam-writhe, murk-blend, and whisper-wind resume;
And you depart with a hush, the underpass's echo-room.

Déjà Vu in the Wabe

'Twas déjà vu, in the wabe of mind's own play;
where clock-flowers gnash and gumble the day;
gleeb-float thoughts twizzle through a silver-schoom,
and every breath repeats its old-new bloom.

The second-hand yawls its tail to meet the sun;
briefly the seen-seen sun again, begun.
twist-twine memories ripple, soft and bright;
a circle-in-time that never leaves the night.

What sip-spark tugs the tongue's recall?
a whisper-wash of could-be, might-flick tall;
we walk the same mead-paths, under the same gray light;
and call it fresh as though it woke this night.

Thus we giggle at the loop, and drink the breeze;
in jabber-wockish murmurs, time eases and flees;
déjà vu, you sly, you glinting friend of mine;
till dawn unknots its yarn and sets the line.

The Desyrepath in the Wabe

'Twas brillig, and the desyrepaths did gyre and gimble in the wabe;
All mimsy were the footlings, and the lamplights outgrabe;
Beware the curb-snarks, and shun the straight-ways' snare;
One desyre-step, and the path begins to speg and slare.

"Come, walklings," cried the sign-gnats, "follow the want-lines through;
Where hedges sigh and grass-dreams glint beneath the dew;
The desyre-walk unfurls its seam of frabjous blue;
And footprints bloom like lanterns on a moony avenue."

The toves did slither, the snark-winds hissed in glee;
The path grew crooked, then clean, a sly peregrine key;
It threads through grass and tile and anchor-tree;
Till every city corner lets the line decide.

So learn, dear wanderer, to heed the seam of chance;
The desyrepath is a living map that grows with glance;
It hums with wind-bells and the footstep's prance;
A shortcut written softly in the soil's own trance.

Mornfog on the Slithy Wold

Twas mornfog, and the slithy roofs did wibble;
Gloam-lamps snerk softly, cobbles giggle;
Mistoodle threads o'er garden gate and thorn,
Rolled pale as smoke that woke the day forlorn.

The borogoves of hedge and lamp-light wink;
Dew-drops fizz in a hush of pale pink.
The sun, a shy ember, yawns and climbs the air,
And morning wears a velvet mist upon the square.

The Brillig Shutter-Tale of the Film

'Twas tulgey in the darkroom, where lens-lamps softly gleam;
The sprocket-snakes coiled slyly, circling the gate of dream;
Emulsion-spirits simmered in barrels of amber light;
And frame-flower shadows blossomed slow in the hush of night.

Aperture-nooks yawed open to drink the shy sun's sigh;
Shutter-whales drifted through the air, and time slid softly by;
Grain-sprites giggled in the ruby-dark, a peppery tune;
While negative-nurels whispered secrets to the hum of the moon.

The film-king's crown glimmered with tepid silver dew;
The darkroom-wind braided memory into light's own brew;
And when the door of darkness opened, dawn would softly grin;
For every frame-born heartbeat woke within the silent film's skin.

Chartlewhim

Under lampglow, creasy charts
went flutter-furl across the floor;
The graticule with gridwise hearts
sang merithreads galore.

The mapwright murmured, “Mind your care—
the Wayward Wyrm-of-Where will twist;
The Crosshatch Gnat nests in the air;
the Drift will fog your wrist.

Trust not the sly Compassnag—
it wheedles north to wobble south;
The Siren-Scale will brag and brag
and salt your journey’s mouth.

He took his brave waywiser then,
the span-pronged measure keen and neat;
He kissed the rose-of-north, and when
it whirred, he loosed his feet.

By loxodromic lanes he strode,
past dentifjords and buckle-sands;
Through contour-choirs the paper flowed
and hissed beneath his hands.

Upon a merithread he paused;
the Misdirrex slid out of shade—
all loop and snare, with tangles gauzed,
its legend-ink afraid.

Its latitude tongue lapped longitude;
its rhumb-lines reeled and writhed;
It wheezed “Here-be” with attitude,
and every route was scythed.

Clack sang the neatline; snap the scale;
he sprang with span and silver rule;
Three arcs he drew, a trisserail,
and pricked its tangle-spool.

He pinned it to a polar pip,
a clean meridian, north to heel;
The Misdirrex gave one last slip
beneath the compass wheel.

He bore the rumor home again
to Mapwright in the midnight glow;
“O legendbright! Tra-loo! Amen!”
cried inks in indigo.

Under lampglow, creasy charts
lay smooth as moons along the floor;
The graticule with gridwise hearts
dreamed merithreads galore.
